article.headline: Clark scores 18 off the Tech bench
article.linkText: Texas Tech makes 23-of-25 FTs in win
article.story:
SAN DIEGO (AP) -- When Texas Tech was struggling, the
third-ranked Lady Raiders relied on Jametra Clark.

Clark provided a big lift for the lethargic Lady Raiders,
scoring a career-high 18 points and keying a huge advantage at the
free throw line in a 65-53 win over Maryland on Sunday night in the
Surf-N-Slam Classic.

Texas Tech struggled through one of its worse games of the
season. But Clark helped save the Lady Raiders, in part, by leading
a first-half run that gave them a lead they never gave up.

"We started out kind of slow, maybe playing a little uptight,"
Clark said. "When I came in, I tried to stay aggressive."

Texas Tech (12-0), which extended its school record for
consecutive wins to start a season, will play host San Diego in the
championship game on Tuesday night. The Toreros defeated Georgetown
65-58.

The Lady Raiders made 23 of 25 free throws to overcome a
season-low in field goal shooting (32.8 percent) and 19 turnovers,
which tied a season high. Maryland made just five of nine free
throws.

Clark, a 52.6 percent free throw shooter coming in, made 12 of
13 free throws.

"I've really been working after practice to get better on my
free throw shooting and I think it paid off," Clark said.

The Lady Raiders also had a 48-33 rebounding edge, including 19
offensive boards.

"I think we won that game at the free throw line and on the
boards," Texas Tech coach Marsha Sharp said. "I was disappointed,
though, in how we executed our offense and reacted to the physical
nature of the game."

Freshman Kalika France scored 18 points to lead Maryland (7-3),
which shot only 37.7 percent from the field and 5-for-9 from the
foul line.

"We were able to play for 40 minutes with a team that doesn't
have any weaknesses," Maryland coach Brenda Frese said. "But
offensively we struggled trying to hit our stride."

Terrapins freshman Shay Doron, the team's leading scorer, was
held to eight points on 3-for-13 shooting.

Clark was instrumental in an 11-0 run that turned a 16-12
deficit into a 23-16 lead with 6:42 left in the first half. The
6-foot-1 sophomore scored seven points in the spurt and the Lady
Raiders never trailed again.

Natalie Ritchie scored 11 points for Texas Tech, including a
pair of 3-pointers in the final six minutes that helped hold off
the Terrapins.

"We didn't play great, but we did what we had to do to win,"
Ritchie said.

Maryland fell to 0-3 this season against ranked teams. The
Terrapins have not beaten a ranked team since the 2000-01 season.
